        "creation_date": 1409463481,
        "answer_count": 2,
        "title": "Android package naming convention",
        "body": "<p>Ok so I know the convention is to put com.domainname.applicationname or something along those lines. What if you don't have a website? <\/p>\n",
        "question_id": 25589243,
        "tags": [
            "java",
            "android",
            "package"
        ],
        "score": -2,
        "closed_reason": "Duplicate",
        "is_answered": true,
        "view_count": 1715
    },
    "question_comments": [],
    "answers": [
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/nhcvo.jpg?s=256",
                "account_id": 255665,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 535871,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/535871/ted-hopp",
                "reputation": 235290,
                "display_name": "Ted Hopp",
                "accept_rate": 84
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 1,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1409463983,
            "creation_date": 1409463983,
            "body": "<p>The purpose of the convention is to reduce the chance of name collisions. The idea is that if you own the \"custombuggywhips.com\" web site, then you are likely going to be the only developer using the package name <code>com.custombuggywhips<\/code>. It also reduces the chance of copyright or trademark problems. Android distinguishes between applications based solely on the application package declared in the manifest, so reducing the chance of collisions is very important.<\/p>\n\n<p>If you don't own a web site, you can still use the convention for a web site that you might someday own and that would likely not be owned by anyone else. Alternatively, you can break with the convention and use a totally made up package name.<\/p>\n\n<p>But the best thing would be to reserve a domain name for your development work and go with that. You don't actually need a web site, just a name that you can call your own.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 25589291,
            "question_id": 25589243
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2a6483f256111c6c5cf8f00b12eb2b5a?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
                "account_id": 4911050,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 3956342,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/3956342/srs",
                "reputation": 647,
                "display_name": "srs",
                "accept_rate": 33
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1409465030,
            "creation_date": 1409463694,
            "body": "<p>You don't require valid website to decide on package name. You can define any packagename which is unique and relevant to your app.<\/p>\n\n<p>For example if your company name is \"test\" then you can have package name as com.example.test<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 25589262,
            "question_id": 25589243,
            "last_edit_date": 1409465030
        }
    ],
